OPTION1:
to Secure, go to config and change PermitRootLogin to no

If not mentioned, you should go to all the app servers

#1:SSH into each app server

ssh banner@stapp03
. -> 2nd server
. -> 3rd server
. -> so on

#2: Edit SSH config

Open the SSH daemon config file:
sudo vi /etc/ssh/sshd_config

#3: Update this setting
PermitRootLogin yes

Change it to:

PermitRootLogin no

If commented out, uncomment and set it to `no`.

#4: Restart SSH service
sudo systemctl restart sshd

If fails,
sudo systemctl restart ssh

#5: Verify setting
grep PermitRootLogin /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Expected:
PermitRootLogin no

OPTION2:
A single command to do this
You can do it from the **jump host in one go** using a loop.

#Run this from `jump-host`:

for h in stapp01 stapp02 stapp03; do
  ssh tony@$h "sudo sed -i 's/^#\?PermitRootLogin.*/PermitRootLogin no/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config && sudo systemctl restart sshd"
done
---

# If different users per server (safer version)

Use this instead:
ssh tony@stapp01 "sudo sed -i 's/^#\?PermitRootLogin.*/PermitRootLogin no/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config && sudo systemctl restart sshd"
ssh steve@stapp02 "sudo sed -i 's/^#\?PermitRootLogin.*/PermitRootLogin no/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config && sudo systemctl restart sshd"
ssh banner@stapp03 "sudo sed -i 's/^#\?PermitRootLogin.*/PermitRootLogin no/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config && sudo systemctl restart sshd"

